{:body
 [[:p
   "On Friday, 11" [:sup "th"]
   " May 2001, Douglas Adams, author of "
   [:cite "The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy"] ", "
   [:cite "Dirk Gently’s Holistic Detective Agency"] ", "
   [:cite "Last Chance to See"] " and " [:cite "The Meaning of Liff"]
   ", died of a heart attack in Santa Barbara,
    California, aged 49."]
  [:p "I grew up with " [:cite "Hitchhiker’s"]
   ". Read all the books multiple times, listened to the radio series on cassette,
    watched the endless reruns of the TV series on UK Gold when we got cable TV in the early 90s."]
  [:p "This post isn’t really about Adams."]
  [:figure
   [:img
    {:alt
     "A GIF of ‘How Many Roads Must a Man Walk Down?’ being played in the terminal"
     :height 787
     :loading "lazy"
     :src "static/42.gif"
     :width 787}]
   [:figcaption
    "Playing "
    [:cite "HOW MANY ROADS MUST A MAN WALK DOWN?"]
    " in "
    [:a
     {:href   "https://davidgriffith.gitlab.io/frotz/"
      :target "_blank"} " Frotz"] ", a terminal Z-code interpreter."]]
  [:h2 "You are standing at the end of a road"]
  [:p
   "On Saturday the 12" [:sup "th"] ", on "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IfMUD"
     :target "_blank"} "ifMUD"] ", "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://www.ifwiki.org/Gunther_Schmidl"
     :target "_blank"} "Gunther Schmidl"] " announced the "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://www.ifwiki.org/DNA_Tribute_Speed-IF"
     :target "_blank"} "DNA Tribute SpeedIF"]
   ". And then on Sunday morning UK time, posted it to the "
   [:code "rec.arts.int-fiction"] " newsgroup, which is where I saw it:"]
  [:div.highlight
   [:div.code
    [:pre [:span "From: \"Gunther Schmidl\" &lt;gschmidl@gmx.at&gt;"] [:br]
     [:span "Newsgroups: rec.arts.int-fiction"] [:br]
     [:span "Subject: [ANN] Douglas Adams Tribute SpeedIF"] [:br]
     [:span "Date: Sun, 13 May 2001 09:32:11 +0100"] [:br]
     [:br]
     [:span
      "In case anyone wants to partake in the Douglas Adams Tribute SpeedIF, this"]
     [:br]
     [:span "is how it works:"] [:br]
     [:br]
     [:span
      "You have until midnight EST today (Sunday, May 13, 2001). Take any"]
     [:br]
     [:span
      "consecutive two-hour block and write a tribute to Douglas Adams in any IF"]
     [:br]
     [:span
      "programming language you want. E-mail me with a download location or the"]
     [:br]
     [:span "file itself when you're done."] [:br]
     [:br]
     [:span "If you take a little longer than 2 hours, no problem."] [:br]
     [:span
      "If you take a little longer than midnight EST, I won't be awake to notice."]
     [:br]
     [:br]
     [:span "-- Gunther"]]]]
  [:p
   "For the uninitiated, “interactive fiction” (IF) is the posh name for what we used to call “text adventures”,
     like "
   [:cite
    [:a
     {:href   "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colossal_Cave_Adventure"
      :target "_blank"} "ADVENT"]]
   ", "
   [:cite
    [:a
     {:href   "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zork"
      :target "_blank"} "Zork"]] " and, indeed, "
   [:cite
    [:a
     {:href
      "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hitchhiker%27s_Guide_to_the_Galaxy_(video_game)"}
     "The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy"]]
   " by Steve Meretzky of Infocom and Douglas Adams himself."]
  [:p
   "“SpeedIF” was, loosely, a semi-regular two hour contest to write a text adventure from start to finish on a
    specific, typically rather silly, theme. Any competition was strictly friendly, and the rules were rarely
    enforced to any great extent."]
  [:p
   "Writing a game in two hours was (and remains) possible due to the availability of  dedicated, free IF tools
    with excellent standard libraries, such as Graham Nelson’s "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://inform-fiction.org/"
     :target "_blank"} "Inform"]
   ". All the infrastructure and world rules are provided, you only need to
   code the locations, objects, and logic unique to the story you want to tell."]
  [:h2 "Twisty little passages"]
  [:p
   "In 2000/01, I was working my internship year at Zurich Financial Services, living alone for the first
    time in my life in a strange flat, in a weird building in Cheltenham."]
  [:p
   "I think it had once been the backstage area of a theatre or something. All the walls were bright golden yellow,
    except the navy blue bedroom with built-in wardrobe doors painted a garish, gloss industrial orange. I don’t
    think there was a single straight line or right angle in the building. The hall curved so severely and
    unexpectedly, I would invariably bounce off the wall on the way to the bathroom or kitchen in the middle of the
    night."]
  [:figure
   [:img
    {:alt     "A photo of the author in Cheltenham in September 2000"
     :height  1467
     :loading "lazy"
     :src     "static/cheltenham1.jpg"
     :width   1024}]
   [:figcaption
    [:p
     "A tiny child moving into a Cheltenham flat in September 2000, laser-focused on the priorities."]
    [:p
     "I still keep cables in one of those blue storage boxes, and that copy of "
     [:cite "The Art of Computer Programming"]
     " is still on my shelf, joined by the first two parts of "
     [:cite "Combinatorial Algorithms"]
     " – the glossy dust cover on Volume 4B is repulsive."]
    [:p
     "Sadly the Amiga A1200, CRT, 56k modem and dual-speed CD-ROM drive were all lost along the way."]]]
  [:p
   "Between a Payroll cock-up and me having no clue whatsoever about tax codes, I was paying about three times
    as much tax as I should have been, on an already low salary."]
  [:p
   "After rent, food, utilities, and getting my only suit dry-cleaned, I’d have maybe £10-20 left at the end of the
    month. Usually enough to buy a novel, typically a fantasy doorstop from Steven Erikson, Robin Hobb, or the collected
    works of one of the old greats like Vance or Zelazny. Or a blister of miniatures from the local Games Workshop –
    Iyanden Ghost Warriors for 3"
   [:sup "rd"] " edition " [:cite "Warhammer 40,000"]
   " that year: the time and effort required to paint a 40 point, metal Eldar Wraithguard bright yellow offering
    surprisingly good bang for buck. I also worked my way through all 11 "
   [:cite "Calvin and Hobbes"] " collections."]
  [:p
   "So my first year away from home, I was poor as a church mouse, rarely socialised, and spent most evenings
    and weekends reading, painting, and programming alone in my absurd flat."]
  [:p
   "Admittedly, a quarter of a century on, that remains pretty much my idea of a good time anyway."]
  [:figure
   [:img
    {:alt     "A photo of the author in Cheltenham, sometime in 2000-2001"
     :height  730
     :loading "lazy"
     :src     "static/cheltenham2.jpg"
     :width   1024}]
   [:figcaption
    [:p
     "A starving waif, presumably in colder months, with the power of Workbench 3.1, a 50MHz 68030, 2+4MB of RAM and a 120MB
     IDE hard drive at his fingertips."]
    [:p
     "For my final year, I finally succumbed and spent my tax refund on a PC, dual booting Win98SE and SuSE
      Linux, so this was really the end of an era. But that Amiga is the computer I used to teach myself C, Perl,
      Vim, 68k assembly, HTML, JavaScript, of course Inform… the list goes on. Not a bad run for a machine
      designed as a budget stopgap, bought in 1992."]
    [:p "I doubt that setup would pass a DSE assessment though."]
    [:p
     "You can tell this photo was taken before May 2001 because the keycaps don’t have
     Dvorak legends written on the front in black felt tip."]]]
  [:h2 "In the beginning the Universe was created"]
  [:p
   "With the typical first-timer’s grandiose vision of writing an Infocom/Level 9 sized adventure, Inform 6
   was one of the things I taught myself that year. I loved text adventures as a kid, growing up with "
   [:cite "The Hobbit"]
   " from Melbourne House and Level 9 Computing’s
    wonderfully atmospheric games like "
   [:cite "Red Moon"] ", " [:cite "The Worm in Paradise"]
   " and their version of " [:cite "ADVENT"] ", " [:cite "Colossal Adventure"]
   " on the Oric Atmos and MSX (a Toshiba HX-10 in my case – these computers probably give you some idea of
   my dad’s ability to pick a winner when it comes to technology)."]
  [:p "Graham Nelson’s superb "
   [:cite]
   [:a
    {:href   "https://inform-fiction.org/manual/index.html"
     :target "_blank"} "Inform Designer’s Manual"]
   ", then in its third edition, provided a comprehensive grounding in not just the how but also the why of
    crafting text adventures."]
  [:p "Predictably, I never finished any of the big ideas I’d once had. "
   [:cite "How Many Roads Must a Man Walk Down?"] " is my only completed game."]
  [:p
   "I’ve always had a soft spot for "
   [:cite "So Long, and Thanks for All the Fish"]
   ". I’ve always found the, oft-criticised, “abrupt authorial intrusions” funny and, outside those pages, it felt
    to me like Adams is having more fun writing a sweet, gentle romance than he’d had with some of the wackier sci-fi
    adventures of the original trilogy. Even though, famously, he in fact wasn’t. At all."]
  [:p
   "My copy of the novel was back home in Sheffield that day, so I ventured into the town centre to track down a new one.
   Consulting historical weather records online, it seems it only hit 25&deg;C on that sunny day in Cheltenham. Maybe it
   was negotiating the crowds, but I was absolutely dripping with sweat by the time I made it home."]
  [:p
   "As I recall, I rattled off the entire development in a single session just shy of the two hour limit."]
  [:p
   "At the time, I don’t remember seeing much reaction by anyone to any of the entries, although I think Gunther
    told me it was “a lovely tribute” when I submitted it. And two and a half decades later, I find myself
    cringing at some of my 21 year old self’s insufferable prose. To me now, any good bits are obvious and minor
    riffs on Adams’ original text."]
  [:p
   "But I discovered today that, 20+ years later, Andrew Schultz in Chicago wrote "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://ifdb.org/viewgame?id=zg8p9khmmhtqwavu&review=74384"
     :target "_blank"} "a very sweet review"]
   ". Just occasionally, the internet can still be as magical a technology as Douglas believed it to be."]
  [:p
   "But this post isn’t about my daft little game either. Not really."]
  [:h2
   "I may not have gone where I intended to go"]
  [:p
   "I’ve been thinking a lot lately about meaningful work. For better or worse, I’ve spent the last 7-8 years of my career
    working on one neverending death march of a project after another. They’ve been critically important to their
    respective organisations, and in many ways satisfying to deliver. But in each case, "
   [:em "the process"]
   " has passed in a numb blur."]
  [:p
   "There’s definitely something about short, sharp periods of creative activity that engenders equally intense memories of
    everything surrounding them. I have similarly vivid reminiscences of the weekend I was inspired to rewrite an ecommerce
    frontend in XHTML, of an evening kit-bashing a Space Marine Librarian, of a mad 36 hour straight crunch responding to a
    change in COVID-19 testing regulations."]
  [:p
   "These aren’t all the most impactful projects I’ve ever worked on by any means (though some were). Sometimes they were
    incredibly stressful experiences."]
  [:p
   "It already feels clichéd to state it aloud but, in particular, I can’t imagine ever having this experience from
    that day I wrote a really fantastic LLM prompt. What they share are clear boundaries. A beginning, a middle, and
    something to point at when I’m done. We obviously can’t abandon the long marches entirely, but I hope to be more
    deliberate about breaking them up. To insist on carving out more afternoons like that Sunday in Cheltenham,
    rather than sleepwalking through months and years waiting for the next one to happen by accident."]
  [:p
   "Anyway."]
  [:p
   "I suspect I still have the original source code backed up somewhere, but most likely in the depths of
    some long-forgotten S3 bucket. If you’d like to play my old game though, you can "
   [:a
    {:download true
     :filename "42.z5"
     :href     "/static/42.z5"} "download it here"]
   ". You’ll need a Z-code interpreter, they’re "
   [:a
    {:href   "https://www.ifwiki.org/FAQ#How_can_I_download_and_play_IF.3F"
     :target "_blank"}
    "freely available for almost every device under the sun."]]
